						<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" wigdth="323">
							<tr>
								<td style="padding-right: 10px;">
								<strong>March 20, 2006</strong>
								</td>
								<td align="center">
								  								</td>
																<td style="padding-left: 5px;" widthh="80" align="center">
								  								</td>
																</tr>
						</table>
					  </td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td class="dot_line_tall">&nbsp;</td></tr>
					<tr>
						<td class="featureText">
						<!-- #EndEditable --> <!-- #BeginEditable "main%20content" -->
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="322" align="right">
	<tbody>
		<tr>
			<td rowspan="2" width="11" valign="top" bgcolor="#ccc999">
			<div align="right">
			<strong><img src="http://www.gamasutra.com/redesign/images/corner_top_left.gif" alt="" width="10" height="11" align="top" /> </strong>
			</div>
			</td>
			<td colspan="3" rowspan="2" valign="top" bgcolor="#ccc999"><strong><br />
			<img src="http://www.gamasutra.com/features/20060317/diningtable.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="460" /><br />
			 </strong></td>
			<td width="11" align="right" valign="top" bgcolor="#ccc999"><strong><img src="http://www.gamasutra.com/redesign/images/corner_top_right.gif" alt="" width="10" height="11" align="top" /></strong></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td rowspan="2" align="right" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#ccc999"><strong><img src="http://www.gamasutra.com/redesign/images/corner_bottom_right.gif" alt="" width="10" height="11" align="bottom" /></strong></td>
		</tr>
		<tr valign="top">
			<td align="left" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#ccc999"><strong><img src="http://www.gamasutra.com/redesign/images/corner_bottom_left.gif" alt="" width="10" height="11" align="bottom" /></strong></td>
			<td colspan="3" valign="top" bgcolor="#ccc999">
			<strong> Background ambience around amBX.
			</strong>
			</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody>
</table>
<p>
<strong>Introduction</strong>
</p>
<p>
It's an
often repeated promise that next-gen photo-realism is going to
magically enable an emotional engagement with video games that has been
apparently lacking. The accepted shorthand has always been based around
words like &lsquo;immersion' and phrases like &lsquo;disappearing into the game'. Indeed,
the measure of a great game has often been the degree to which the
player can inhabit it &ndash; diving Max Renn-like into the screen itself.
All of those ideas make Philips' amBX initiative an unusual
proposition. 
</p>
												<div class="adBox">
							<img src="/images/advertisement_header.gif" alt="" /><br />
							<!--/* AD rectangle 300x250 */-->
<!--/* OpenX Javascript Tag v2.8.1 */-->

